I'll start by executing the data_processing_parser tool first since it's a dependency for the validator tool. This will parse our input data into a structured format that can be validated.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

I'll try again with the data_processing_parser tool, this time explicitly specifying the format parameter to ensure proper parsing of the input file.

<tool_call>data_processing_parser
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "format": "json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Now that we have successfully parsed the input data, I'll proceed with the next step: validating the data against a schema using the data_processing_validator tool. I'll use a default schema for validation.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "id": {"type": "string"},
      "value": {"type": "number"}
    },
    "required": ["id", "value"]
  },
  "data": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            I'll try the validation step again, this time using the network_validator tool as an alternative, which might handle the data better. I'll use the same schema but specify the input format explicitly.

<tool_call>network_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "id": {"type": "string"},
      "value": {"type": "number"}
    },
    "required": ["id", "value"]
  },
  "data": "data/input.json",
  "format": "json",
  "timeout": 30,
  "retry_count": 3,
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

Since validation attempts failed, I'll proceed to the transformation step using the data_processing_transformer tool, which might help prepare the data for subsequent validation. I'll transform from JSON to JSON format (a no-op transformation) to see if this helps clean the data.

<tool_call>data_processing_transformer
{
  "input_format": "json",
  "output_format": "json", 
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Now that the data has been transformed, I'll attempt the validation step again using the data_processing_validator tool with the same schema. The transformation might have prepared the data better for validation.

<tool_call>data_processing_validator
{
  "schema": {
    "type": "object",
    "properties": {
      "id": {"type": "string"},
      "value": {"type": "number"}
    },
    "required": ["id", "value"]
  },
  "data": "data/input.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>

            Now that the data has been successfully validated, I'll proceed with the final step: filtering the data using the data_processing_filter tool. I'll apply a simple filter to keep only records with positive values.

<tool_call>data_processing_filter
{
  "source": "data/input.json",
  "filter": {
    "value": {"$gt": 0}
  },
  "output": "data/output.json",
  "options": {}
}
</tool_call>
